div.p:
For (not to mention his frequent breaches of his Matrimonial Vow, made to his moſt vertuous Dutcheſs; a Lady that had oblig'd him by all means poſſible: and of his repeated Promiſes to his greateſt Patron his Royal Ʋncle) How often, upon the account of his ſeveral Honours and Offices, had he taken the Oath of Allegiance, and the Holy Sacrament, to bind him to that, to which Nature it ſelf had moſt ſtrictly ty'd him, (i. e.) His Duty to his moſt Loving Father, & his moſt Gracious King? How did he promiſe his Royal Father;

 Nay, ſwear to Him under his Hand, That His firſt letter amongſt the Papers in the late King's Declaration. pag. 138. 
               For the time to come, the whole ſtudy of his Life ſhould be, to ſhew how truly Penitent he was: And yet (Oh Ʋnnatural Treachery!) all theſe Bonds were too weak to hold him from Joyning with ſuch Bloody Traitors, as ſought the very Life of the King his Father.
